    s.c = 'a';
    std::cout << "Value of c: " << s.c << "\n";
    s.d = 3.14;
    std::cout << "Value of d: " << s.d << "\n";
    std::cout << "Value of i: " << s.i << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```
In this example, we define a struct called MyStruct that contains an anonymous union with three members. We can access the members directly without using the union name, as if they were members of the struct itself.

The main difference between a union and a struct is that a union can only hold one value at a time, while a struct can hold multiple values simultaneously. Additionally, changing the value of one member of a union affects the values of the other members, while changing the value of one member of a struct does not affect the values of the other members.

In summary, unions are a way to store different data types in the same memory location, with only one member accessible at a time. Anonymous unions are unions defined inside a struct or class, with direct access to their members.

